{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Q8Y8u2oV6iJouqHptapyu5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me implement the feature specification. I'll need to:\n\n1. Add `schemars` dependency to Cargo.toml\n2. Add `FailureClass` enum and contract identity types to `shared/domain.rs`\n3. Add error variants to `shared/error.rs`\n4. Create `contexts/workflow_composition/payloads.rs` - typed payload structs\n5. Create `contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` - StageContract, registry, evaluation\n6. Create `contexts/workflow_composition/renderers.rs` - deterministic Markdown renderers\n\n\n7. Update `contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs` to expose the new modules\n8. Register test modules in `tests/unit.rs`\n9. Add unit tests for stage contracts and renderers\n10. Create a conformance test feature file for stage contracts\n\nThe key design decision is grouping stages into payload families: planning-style stages like `prompt_review`, `planning`, `docs_plan`, and `ci_plan` form one family, while execution and update stages form another.\n\nEach stage gets a `StageContract` that handles schema validation, semantic validation, and rendering in that order. I'm using `schemars` to generate JSON schemas from Rust types, and implementing deterministic Markdown renderers so the same payload always produces identical output. For failures, I need to track `TransportFailure`, `SchemaValidationFailure`, `DomainValidationFailure`, `Timeout`, `Cancellation`, and `QaReviewOutcomeFailure`.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the payload structures for each stage type. Planning stages need fields for problem framing, assumptions, proposed work items, and readiness assessment. Execution stages require a change summary, ordered steps, validation evidence, and risk tracking. Validation and review stages need an outcome enum, supporting evidence, findings, and follow-up items when approval isn't clean. The contract then validates each payload against its schema and semantic rules.\n\nFor validation, I'll use `schemars` to generate JSON schemas from the Rust types and `jsonschema` to validate incoming payloads against those schemas. The contract will also run domain-specific semantic validation before rendering the payload to Markdown deterministically, returning either a validated bundle with the artifact or an error.\n\nDefining the payload types... Defining the payload structures... Defining the contract structures...\n\nI'm reconsidering the approach here—instead of the enum-based payload structure, a trait-based design would be cleaner for handling the validation pipeline. The key steps are deserializing JSON to the right type, running semantic checks on the typed payload, and rendering it to markdown. Let me think through how to structure this with traits so each stage can define its own validation logic and rendering behavior. Defining the contract structure with a stage ID and family enum to identify which payload type to use, then implementing methods to generate the appropriate JSON schema and evaluate incoming data through schema validation before deserialization and semantic checks.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the validation approach—I could rely on serde's deserialization for schema enforcement, but I think using jsonschema for explicit JSON Schema validation alongside serde would be more robust and aligned with the spec requirements. I'm reconsidering the approach—serde deserialization alone won't fully satisfy the schema validation requirement, so I need to use both `schemars` for generating the JSON Schema and `jsonschema` for explicit validation against it. I'll go with conservative versions that have been stable for a while and just try compiling to see what works. I'm settling on this approach and ready to start building it out. Let me sketch the module structure: payloads will hold the data types and enums, contracts will contain the validation logic and registry, renderers will handle the markdown output, and I'll add the necessary error types and domain classes to the shared modules.\n\nNow I'm refining the concrete payload structures—thinking through what fields each stage actually needs and whether to include contextual information like stage_id in the payload itself or keep it separate since the contract already knows which stage it's evaluating.\n\nDefining the payload types... I need to clarify how validation outcomes map to contract results—when a payload passes structural and semantic validation but has a non-passing outcome like RequestChanges or Rejected, that should map to QaReviewOutcomeFailure rather than a schema failure. This means the contract evaluation needs to distinguish between structural success with a passing outcome versus structural success with a non-passing outcome. Defining the result structure...\n\nThe key insight is that non-passing QA/review outcomes should return the validated payload and artifact together, but mark the failure class so the workflow engine can distinguish them from clean passes. I'm considering whether to use an optional failure class field or a separate enum variant for outcome failures, though the spec constraint about returning either a complete bundle or an error suggests the enum approach might be cleaner. Defining the result enum...\n\nI'm thinking through what the workflow engine actually needs to know: whether contract evaluation succeeded, and if so, whether there was a non-passing review outcome. So I'll use a single `Success` variant that carries an optional failure class, keeping the distinction between hard errors and outcome failures clean. I've settled on the structure for `EvalSuccess` and `ContractError` — now I need to organize everything into the proper files. I'm going to take a pragmatic approach and start writing out the implementation, beginning with adding the schema generation dependency, then defining the core domain types, error variants, and payload structures across the shared modules.\n\nWriting the contract system...\n\nFor the renderers, I need to ensure deterministic Markdown output—no timestamps, random elements, or unsorted fields. Let me sketch out what each stage's rendered output should look like: Planning includes problem framing, assumptions, proposed work items, and a readiness assessment with risks; Execution captures the change summary, ordered steps with status indicators, and validation evidence; Validation documents the checks performed, their results, and any issues found.\n\nI'm realizing the stage name comes from the StageId rather than the payload itself, so the renderer needs both pieces to construct the heading properly. Also, I should stick to \"cycle\" terminology throughout instead of \"iteration\" or \"loop\" to match the spec's canonical language.\n\nNow I need to finalize the implementation and make sure the JSON Schema is solid. Continuing with the match statement to map each stage to its contract family, then implementing the evaluation logic that will validate the raw JSON against the appropriate contract rules. I'm parsing through the spec more carefully now. The key distinction is that QA review outcome failures are workflow-level issues, not contract violations—they don't prevent the bundle from being returned like schema or domain failures do. So the evaluation succeeds with the bundle intact, but the caller gets flagged that there's an outcome failure to handle separately.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement this. For the JSON schema piece, I'll use `schemars` to derive schemas from the Rust types and rely on `serde_json` deserialization for validation—if the JSON doesn't match the type structure, it fails naturally. This keeps things clean without pulling in a heavy validation library.\n\nAdding schemars dependency...\n\nDefining the domain types... I'm realizing I need to think through the error handling architecture more carefully. The spec wants schem